    A visitor for both constraints and expressions. Ideally, constraints should be an extension of expressions themselves, but, alas!, they are not. Each node N in the expression tree (which may be a DAG) has an operator, zero or more operands O1, O2, O3, ..., and implements a routine called "accept(ConstraintExpressionVisitor visitor)" which calls the methods of this visitor in the following way:
    1. When node N is encountered, visitor.preVisit(N).
    2. Before the first operand O1 is visited, visitor.inVisitBefore(N, O1) is called.
    3. O1 is visited.
    4. visitor.inVisitAfter(N, O1) is called.
    5. Before the second operand O2 is visited, visitor.inVisitBefore(N, O2) is called.
    6. O2 is visited.
    7. visitor.inVisitAfter(N, O2) is called.
    8. ...
    9. Before the operand Ok is visited, visitor.inVisitBefore(N, Ok) is called.
    10. Ok is visited.
    11. visitor.inVisitAfter(N, Ok) is called.
    12. Finally, once all the operands have been visited, visitor.postVisit(N) is called.
    For the moment, visitor.inVisitBefore(...) and visitor.inVisitAfter(...) routines are not implemented. They would add another 1134 methods to this class, and although it would not impact runtime efficiency, it does seem like overkill.
